english:
  title: Elegiac Edict for the Bright King
  author: Choe Hong-yun
  language: eng
  text: |-
    In the third year of Taewhoa, in the eleventh month of the Year of the Water Dog, on the seventeenth day of the first moon, the Bright King, the Great Sovereign of Filial Devotion, passed from the Palace of Nurturing Harmony. According to ritual, on the second day of the intercalary eleventh month, he was conveyed to the Tomb of Wisdom.

    At that time, clouds hung heavy with sorrow over the Southern Ridge, while mist wept upon the Northern Burial Ground. The spirit-carriage rolled through veils of azure toward the shadowed depths of the tomb's passage. The pines and cranes cried out in lament, their mourning touching the vast grief of heaven. The fish in the pools leaped and trembled, remembering the compassion that once slackened the net. How can this humble heart endure such anguish? Thus do I lament the breaking of the goose-line formation, and offer libations of fragrant ant-wine. By command, I compose these elegiac words and present this precious edict.

    The words are these:

    Once our Great Ancestor arose in an auspicious age, subdued the rebel lands, and established the great foundation. Successive rulers inherited and perfected this realm, bringing utmost peace and harmony. The generations reached the Resolute Temple, and the people flourished like fish in schools. Yet when indulgence held sway, the people's hearts departed. Then came our Serene Elder Brother, answering the hopes of the multitude. From his modest dwelling he rose suddenly to reign above the people. Moved by their weariness, he bestowed compassion and nurture. His transforming influence spread far and near, and songs of praise filled every street and alley.

    When years brought him to his seventieth spring, his spirit grew weary of diligent rule. He withdrew to become the Sovereign Emeritus, preserving both body and essence. From my small self to all the common people, we prayed for longevity, hoping he would endure as long as heaven and earth.

    Yet how could it be that in a single evening he turned suddenly toward the Nine Springs? Human life's length is measured by Heaven's hand alone. The sacred vessel passed to its rightful heir, and on white clouds he ascended to the Emperor's realm.

    Alas! The oracle confirmed auspicious signs; the hidden palace was opened in blessed ground. The immortal chariot recedes—a sigh stirs the wind. The people of the capital weep—their tears fall as rain.

    Thus it is: the way that mortals hold most precious is the harmony and unity of brothers. Now I walk alone in solitude, and my heart cannot find peace.
  footnotes:
  - key: ''
    value: 'Northern Burial Ground: This refers to the ancient practice of burial at the Northern Ridge near Luoyang in China, a traditional metaphor for the grave itself.'
  - key: ''
    value: 'The Nine Springs: A poetic reference to the underworld or the realm of the dead in East Asian tradition.'
